# New session create

`C-n` creates a session named by the query. Without repo context, the new tmux
session inherits the current working directory and has no repo metadata.

    :bins jj tmux

> [!NOTE]
> 'jj', and 'tmux' are available.

    :t rename-session -t 0 runner (success)
    :t new-session -d -s ui "sesh" (success)
    :t resize-window -t ui:0 -x 120 -y 10 (success)
    :pane ui:0.0
    :settle -d 2s (settled)

Type a unique session name and create it with `C-n`.

    :k zeta
    :snap

```terminal
session: zeta
  0/2 | [C-r] repo: none | [C-n] new
                                                                                                                       ┃
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────






```

    :k C-n
    :snap -d 2s

```terminal
sh$























```

The client should switch to the newly-created session, and no repo metadata
should be attached.

    :t display-message -p '#{client_session}' (success)

```
zeta
```

    :t list-sessions -F '#{session_name}:#{@sesh.repo}' (success)

```
runner:
zeta:
```

